West 163rd Street, north side, west from Fort Washington Ave., showing the southern extremity of the grounds of the New York Institution for the Deaf. This set consists of 3 views, No. 3 of which is in the opposite
direction, being eastward from Riverside Drive.
June 15, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.

719814f-b.title: Manhattan: Fort Washington Aven - 163rd Street (West)
719814f-b.text:
Fort Washington Ave., north from West 163rd Street, and showing upon the west side of same, the New York Institution for the Deaf extending to 165th Street. Note the tower of the George Washington Bridge through the trees. This set consists of 3 views, Nos. 2 and 3 being from a view point slightly northward to show prominently the Vocational School at the
S.W. corner of 165th Street.
June 15, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.
719814f-b.folder: Fort Washington Aven & 163rd Street (West), Manhattan, NY

719815f-a.title: Manhattan: Fort Washington Aven - 163rd Street (West)
719815f-a.text:
Fort Washington Ave., west side, from West 163rd (left) to 165th (right) Streets, showing the buildings and grounds of the New York Institution for the Deaf extending westward to Riverside Drive. These
2 views form a panorama.
June 16, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.

E. 163rd Street, west from Washington to Brook Avenues. The north side of the street is occupied by a gasoline station and two frame dwellings. The south side of the street is the base
